@SR4ven The updated version is pushed. Description of changes here.

As you've gathered, `mutations()` can yield a callable that mutates the "normal" value, which may be dynamic.

The previous approach was doing some weird stuff with closures inside the mutations() generator:
```python
        for fuzz_bytes in self._fuzz_strings_1byte:
            i = 0
            keep_going = True
            while keep_going:

                def f(value):
                    nonlocal keep_going
                    if i < len(value):
                        return value[:i] + fuzz_bytes + value[i + 1 :]
                    else:
                        keep_going = False

                yield f
                i += 1
```
The idea was that we wanted to mutate the "value", which can change between protocol runs. BUT, the number of mutations depends on the length of the value. So I did this weird thing with the closure `f` and `nonlocal keepgoing` (nonlocal means the closure can write to the value and the parent function will see it. This still left me with two problems: 1) At the end of the function, we didn't have a value to return. 2) The usage gets weird, as the behavior of the generator depends on the function it yields being called before the next generator iteration.

The compromise I settled on was to have mutations() accept a "default value" (this is how I had it in one of the previous iterators before the PR). So now there's a distinction between "default value" and "normal value". The "default value" must be provided in the protocol definition -- this is either the value as normally provided, or the "default_value" of a `TestCaseSessionReference` object. The "normal value" is usually the same as the default value, but if `TestCaseSessionReference` is used, the normal value is the value referenced by `TestCaseSessionReference`.

Now the `Bytes.mutations()` function uses the default value to control its iteration loops, but it still yields a function that mutates the "normal value".

