Sorry for not commenting on this in the design doc earlier, but it only occurred to me just now...

I know we've typically emitted these in the past like what's currently being done here, but I was wondering if we should use [`const enums`](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/enums.html#const-enums) instead:

```typescript
export const enum ContainerColor {
    Red = "red",
    Blue = "blue",
    Yellow = "yellow",
}

export const enum ContainerSize {
    FourInch = 4,
    SixInch = 6,
    EightInch = 8,
}

export const enum RubberTreeVariety {
    /** A burgundy rubber tree. */
    Burgundy = "Burgundy",
    /** A ruby rubber tree. */
    Ruby = "Ruby",
    /** A tineke rubber tree. */
    Tineke = "Tineke",
}
```

Unfortunately, there appears to be a downside: the value would have to be specified as `RubberTreeVariety.Burgundy` rather than `"Burgundy"`.

```typescript
export interface RubberTreeArgs {
    readonly type?: RubberTreeVariety;
}

const a: RubberTreeArgs = {
    type: RubberTreeVariety.Burgundy, // Works
};

const b: RubberTreeArgs = {
    type: "Burgundy", // Doesn't work
};
```

To solve this, I was wondering if there was a built-in way in TypeScript to lookup the type of the enum property values, but there doesn't look like there's a way to do that, so we'd have to do something like:

```typescript
export const enum RubberTreeVariety {
    /** A burgundy rubber tree. */
    Burgundy = "Burgundy",
    /** A ruby rubber tree. */
    Ruby = "Ruby",
    /** A tineke rubber tree. */
    Tineke = "Tineke",
}

export type RubberTreeVarietyValues = "Burgundy" | "Ruby" | "Tineke";

export interface RubberTreeArgs {
    readonly type?: RubberTreeVariety | RubberTreeVarietyValues;
}
```

But having to have different named types (`RubberTreeVariety` and `RubberTreeVarietyValues`) is not ideal. So not really loving that.

However, this exploration led me to the following blog post: https://www.designcise.com/web/tutorial/is-it-possible-to-allow-literal-string-values-with-typeScripts-enum-type

I think we should consider doing something along the lines of that post:

```typescript
export const ContainerColor = {
    Red: "red",
    Blue: "blue",
    Yellow: "yellow",
} as const;

export type ContainerColor = (typeof ContainerColor)[keyof typeof ContainerColor]; // "red" | "blue" | "yellow"

export const ContainerSize = {
    FourInch: 4,
    SixInch: 6,
    EightInch: 8,
} as const;

export type ContainerSize = (typeof ContainerSize)[keyof typeof ContainerSize]; // 4 | 6 | 8

export const RubberTreeVariety = {
    /** A burgundy rubber tree. */
    Burgundy: "Burgundy",
    /** A ruby rubber tree. */
    Ruby: "Ruby",
    /** A tineke rubber tree. */
    Tineke: "Tineke",
} as const;

export type RubberTreeVariety = (typeof RubberTreeVariety)[keyof typeof RubberTreeVariety]; // "Burgundy" | "Ruby" | "Tineke"
```

It allows both of these uses:

```typescript
// Both work.
const a: RubberTreeArgs = {
    type: RubberTreeVariety.Burgundy, // Works
};
const b: RubberTreeArgs = {
    type: "Burgundy", // Works
};
```

And doesn't require two different type names.

And provides a cleaner way of grouping the constants together, improving discoverability, etc.

